## 15. Polymorphism - Tutorial specs for AI (C++)

### 15.1 Topic - Polymorphism Intro (Meaning + two types)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: templates; STL containers; `new/delete`; smart pointers; exceptions; operator overloading; multiple inheritance; virtual inheritance.
  - Do **not** go deep into memory model, vtables, or `typeid`/RTTI.
  - Keep code beginner-friendly: `class`, `public`, simple functions, `cout`, `string`, `int`, `float`.

- **Core concepts**
  - Polymorphism means **one name, many forms**.
  - In C++ (beginner view):
    - **Compile-time polymorphism**: function overloading (decided by compiler).
    - **Run-time polymorphism**: virtual functions + overriding (decided at runtime).
  - Teach: first understand the idea with tiny examples, then implement it in later topics.

- **Mermaid flow (tiny)**

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A[Polymorphism] --> B[Compile-time]
  A --> C[Run-time]
  B --> D[Function overloading]
  C --> E[virtual + override]
```

- **Lesson structure requirements (same drill)**
  - Concept -> MCQ -> codeblock_rearranging -> fill_in_blanks
  - Use very small code snippets per lesson.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Same function name, different parameter lists (preview)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

float add(float a, float b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    cout << add(2, 3) << "\n";
    cout << add(2.5f, 3.5f) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Same method name, different parameter counts (preview)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Printer {
public:
    void show(int x) {
        cout << "int: " << x << "\n";
    }

    void show(int x, int y) {
        cout << "two ints: " << x << ", " << y << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Printer p;
    p.show(10);
    p.show(10, 20);
    return 0;
}
```

---

### 15.2 Topic - Compile-time Polymorphism (Function Overloading)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: virtual functions; `override`; base pointers; runtime dispatch; pure virtual; abstract classes; inheritance as the main focus.
  - Do **not** introduce: templates; default parameters; function pointers; lambdas.
  - Do **not** introduce operator overloading here.

- **What to teach**
  - Overloading = same function name, different parameter list.
  - Return type alone cannot overload (mention with one counterexample).
  - Keep overloads meaningful and beginner-friendly.

- **Mini-lesson sequence (4-6 lessons)**
  - L1: Overload `add(int,int)` vs `add(float,float)`
  - L2: Overload with different count: `area(int side)` vs `area(int l, int w)`
  - L3: Overload in a class: `print(int)` vs `print(string)`
  - L4: Common mistake: ambiguous call (use explicit `f` for float)
  - L5: Practice: build `calculate(...)` overloads (sum/product)

- **MCQ ideas**
  - Which calls match which overload?
  - Is `int f(int)` and `float f(int)` valid overloading? (No.)

- **Code-rearrange ideas**
  - Rearrange overloaded function definitions + `main()` calls to compile.

- **Fill-in-the-blanks ideas**
  - Fill parameter types (`int` vs `float`) and suffix `f` in `2.5f`.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. add() overloads
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

float add(float a, float b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    int x = add(10, 20);
    float y = add(1.5f, 2.5f);
    cout << x << "\n";
    cout << y << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. area() overloads (count differs)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int area(int side) {
    return side * side;
}

int area(int length, int width) {
    return length * width;
}

int main() {
    cout << area(5) << "\n";
    cout << area(4, 6) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Class method overloading
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Report {
public:
    void print(int marks) {
        cout << "Marks: " << marks << "\n";
    }

    void print(string name) {
        cout << "Name: " << name << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Report r;
    r.print("Riya");
    r.print(92);
    return 0;
}
```

- **Key points**
  - Overloading is decided at **compile-time**.
  - Parameter list must differ (type/count/order).

- **Common mistakes**
  - Confusing overloading with overriding.
  - Writing `add(2.5, 3.5)` without `f` and getting an unexpected match.

- **Best practices**
  - Keep overloads consistent in meaning (same “intent”).
  - Prefer clear names over too many overloads.

---

### 15.3 Topic - Run-time Polymorphism (Virtual Functions + Overriding)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: templates; operator overloading; exceptions; RTTI (`typeid`, `dynamic_cast`); virtual inheritance; multiple inheritance.
  - Do **not** discuss vtables, memory layout, or deep “how virtual works internally”.
  - Avoid `new/delete`. Use stack objects and references/pointers that point to existing objects.

- **What to teach**
  - Overriding happens in inheritance: child provides its own version of a base method.
  - `virtual` in base enables runtime dispatch when using base pointer/reference.
  - Use `override` keyword for clarity.
  - Show the difference between:
    - Calling through a **base object** (base version),
    - Calling through **base reference/pointer** to a derived object (derived version if virtual).

- **Mermaid flow (runtime dispatch)**

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A[Base pointer/reference] --> B{virtual?}
  B -->|Yes| C[Call derived override]
  B -->|No| D[Call base method]
```

- **Mini-lesson sequence (4-6 lessons)**
  - L1: DemoParent/DemoChild with `virtual displayRole()`
  - L2: Same demo without `virtual` to show “wrong” behavior (short contrast)
  - L3: User -> Student/Teacher overrides `showProfile()`
  - L4: Vehicle -> Car/Bike/Truck overrides `showType()`
  - L5: Common mistakes: forgetting `virtual`, signature mismatch, not using `override`

- **Example snippets (same examples, multiple properties, multiline methods)**

```cpp
// 1. Demo: base pointer calls derived method (virtual)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class DemoParent {
public:
    virtual void show() {
        cout << "DemoParent show()\n";
    }
};

class DemoChild : public DemoParent {
public:
    void show() override {
        cout << "DemoChild show()\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    DemoChild child;
    DemoParent* ptr = &child;
    ptr->show();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. User -> Student/Teacher: override showProfile()
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class User {
public:
    string name;
    int age;
    string city;

    void setUser(string n, int a, string c) {
        name = n;
        age = a;
        city = c;
    }

    virtual void showProfile() {
        cout << "User: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", City: " << city << "\n";
    }
};

class Student : public User {
public:
    int rollNo;
    string course;

    void setStudent(int r, string crs) {
        rollNo = r;
        course = crs;
    }

    void showProfile() override {
        cout << "Student: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", City: " << city << "\n";
        cout << "RollNo: " << rollNo << ", Course: " << course << "\n";
    }
};

class Teacher : public User {
public:
    string subject;
    int experienceYears;

    void setTeacher(string sub, int exp) {
        subject = sub;
        experienceYears = exp;
    }

    void showProfile() override {
        cout << "Teacher: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", City: " << city << "\n";
        cout << "Subject: " << subject << ", Experience: " << experienceYears << " years\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    s.setUser("Aman", 18, "Delhi");
    s.setStudent(101, "C++");

    Teacher t;
    t.setUser("Neha", 29, "Pune");
    t.setTeacher("Math", 6);

    User* p1 = &s;
    User* p2 = &t;

    p1->showProfile();
    p2->showProfile();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Vehicle -> Car/Bike/Truck: override showType()
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Vehicle {
public:
    string brand;
    int wheels;
    int maxSpeed;

    void setVehicle(string b, int w, int speed) {
        brand = b;
        wheels = w;
        maxSpeed = speed;
    }

    virtual void showType() {
        cout << "Vehicle: " << brand << ", Wheels: " << wheels << ", MaxSpeed: " << maxSpeed << "\n";
    }
};

class Car : public Vehicle {
public:
    int doors;
    string fuel;

    void setCar(int d, string f) {
        doors = d;
        fuel = f;
    }

    void showType() override {
        cout << "Car: " << brand << ", Wheels: " << wheels << ", MaxSpeed: " << maxSpeed << "\n";
        cout << "Doors: " << doors << ", Fuel: " << fuel << "\n";
    }
};

class Bike : public Vehicle {
public:
    int cc;
    bool hasGear;

    void setBike(int c, bool gear) {
        cc = c;
        hasGear = gear;
    }

    void showType() override {
        cout << "Bike: " << brand << ", Wheels: " << wheels << ", MaxSpeed: " << maxSpeed << "\n";
        cout << "CC: " << cc << ", HasGear: ";
        if (hasGear) {
            cout << "Yes";
        } else {
            cout << "No";
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }
};

class Truck : public Vehicle {
public:
    int loadCapacityKg;
    int axles;

    void setTruck(int cap, int ax) {
        loadCapacityKg = cap;
        axles = ax;
    }

    void showType() override {
        cout << "Truck: " << brand << ", Wheels: " << wheels << ", MaxSpeed: " << maxSpeed << "\n";
        cout << "Load: " << loadCapacityKg << " kg, Axles: " << axles << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Car c;
    c.setVehicle("Toyota", 4, 180);
    c.setCar(4, "Petrol");

    Bike b;
    b.setVehicle("Honda", 2, 120);
    b.setBike(160, true);

    Truck tr;
    tr.setVehicle("Tata", 6, 90);
    tr.setTruck(8000, 3);

    Vehicle* v1 = &c;
    Vehicle* v2 = &b;
    Vehicle* v3 = &tr;

    v1->showType();
    v2->showType();
    v3->showType();
    return 0;
}
```

- **MCQ ideas**
  - If base method is not `virtual`, which version runs when calling through `Base*`?
  - What does `override` help catch? (Signature mismatch.)

- **Code-rearrange ideas**
  - Rearrange: base class with `virtual`, derived override, base pointer calls.

- **Fill-in-the-blanks ideas**
  - Fill `virtual`, `override`, and pointer type `Vehicle*`.

- **Key points**
  - Runtime polymorphism needs: **inheritance + virtual + overriding + base pointer/reference**.

- **Common mistakes**
  - Forgetting `virtual` in base.
  - Changing the function signature accidentally (so it doesn’t override).
  - Expecting polymorphism when calling via a base **object** (not pointer/reference).

- **Best practices**
  - Use `override` on derived methods.
  - Keep method names and signatures consistent across base/derived.


### 5.2 `for` loop - Tutorial spec for AI (C++)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: functions; recursion; arrays; strings (beyond basic console input/output); pointers; classes/objects/structs; enums.
  - Do **not** include star/shape patterns in this section.
  - Use only: variables, `std::cout`, `std::cin`, `if`/`else`, `while`, `do-while`, and `for` loops.

> **Pending tutorials requested here**: create **3"4 `for`-loop tutorials**, each with **4"6 lessons**, covering counting, numeric patterns (sum, factorial, tables, power), and nested loops (numeric only). Follow the lesson structure: concept -> mcq -> codeblock_rearranging -> fill_in_blanks, with mermaid flowcharts, `keyPoints`, `commonMistakes`, `bestPractices`, and multiple small code snippets.

#### 5.2.A Topic - `for` Loop Basics (Counting)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: functions; recursion; arrays; strings (beyond basic console input/output); pointers; classes/objects/structs; enums; star/shape patterns.
  - Use only: loops, counters, and console I/O with `cout`/`cin`.
- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Print numbers from 1 to 100
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    for (int i = 1; i <= 100; i++) {
        cout << i << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Print numbers from 100 down to 1
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    for (int i = 100; i >= 1; i--) {
        cout << i << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Print from user start to user end (inclusive)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int start, end;
    cout << "Enter start: ";
    cin >> start;
    cout << "Enter end: ";
    cin >> end;

    for (int i = start; i <= end; i++) {
        cout << i << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Even numbers from 2 to 100
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    for (int i = 2; i <= 100; i += 2) {
        cout << i << " ";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

- **Exercises / other lesson types**
  - MCQ: identify init/condition/increment; predict output.
  - Code-rearrange: build a 1->100 loop, 100->1 loop.
  - Fill-in-the-blanks: missing init/condition/increment.

#### 5.2.B Topic - `for` Loop for Numeric Patterns (Sum, Factorial, Tables, Power)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: functions; recursion; arrays; strings (beyond basic console input/output); pointers; classes/objects/structs; enums; star/shape patterns.
  - Use only: loops, accumulators, and console I/O.
- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 5. Sum 1 to n
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter n: ";
    cin >> n;

    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        sum += i;
    }
    cout << "Sum = " << sum << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 6. Factorial of n
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter n: ";
    cin >> n;

    long long fact = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        fact *= i;
    }
    cout << "Factorial of " << n << " = " << fact << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 7. Multiplication table (1 to 10)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter a number: ";
    cin >> n;

    for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
        cout << n << " x " << i << " = " << (n * i) << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 8. Compute a^b using repeated multiplication
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int a, b;
    cout << "Enter base (a): ";
    cin >> a;
    cout << "Enter exponent (b): ";
    cin >> b;

    long long result = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= b; i++) {
        result *= a;
    }
    cout << a << "^" << b << " = " << result << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 9. Sum of even numbers from 1 to n
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter n: ";
    cin >> n;

    int sumEven = 0;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i += 2) {
        sumEven += i;
    }

    cout << "Sum of even numbers = " << sumEven << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

- **Exercises / other lesson types**
  - MCQ: spot off-by-one and accumulator reset mistakes.
  - Code-rearrange: assemble sum/table/power loops.
  - Fill-in-the-blanks: missing bounds or accumulator initialization.

#### 5.2.C Topic - Nested `for` Loops (Numeric Only)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: functions; recursion; arrays; strings (beyond basic console input/output); pointers; classes/objects/structs; enums.
  - Do **not** use star or shape patterns; use numeric grids/tables only.
  - Use only: nested `for` loops with numeric output.
- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 9. Print a 3x4 grid of (row,col)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    for (int row = 1; row <= 3; row++) {
        for (int col = 1; col <= 4; col++) {
            cout << "(" << row << "," << col << ") ";
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 10. Tables 1 to 5 (each 1 to 10)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    for (int n = 1; n <= 5; n++) {
        cout << "Table of " << n << ":\n";
        for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
            cout << n << " x " << i << " = " << (n * i) << "\n";
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 11. Factorials 1 to 10 using nested for
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    for (int n = 1; n <= 10; n++) {
        long long fact = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            fact *= i;
        }
        cout << "Factorial of " << n << " = " << fact << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

- **Exercises / other lesson types**
  - MCQ: iterations of inner vs outer loop; final value reasoning.
  - Code-rearrange: assemble nested loop program (tables of tables / factorials 1 to 10).
  - Fill-in-the-blanks: outer/inner bounds and inner reset.

