## 7. Recursion - Tutorial specs for AI (C++)

#### 7.1 Topic - Recursion Basics (hello Codehub, counters, simple printing)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: arrays; strings as parameters; pointers; references; classes/objects; dynamic memory; return-value recursion for computation (sum/factorial return).
  - Use only: recursion with `void` functions, base cases, and printing/counting with `cout`.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Infinite recursion example (DO NOT RUN AS-IS)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void helloRec() {
    cout << "Hello Codehub\n";
    helloRec();
}

int main() {
    // helloRec(); // calling this will keep calling itself until the program crashes
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Controlled recursion using a counter
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void helloRec(int count) {
    if (count == 0) {
        return;
    }
    cout << "Hello Codehub\n";
    helloRec(count - 1);
}

int main() {
    helloRec(5);
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Print from n down to 0 using recursion
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void printDown(int n) {
    if (n < 0) {
        return;
    }
    cout << n << "\n";
    printDown(n - 1);
}

int main() {
    printDown(5);
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Print from start down to end
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void printDownRange(int start, int end) {
    if (start < end) {
        return;
    }
    cout << start << "\n";
    printDownRange(start - 1, end);
}

int main() {
    printDownRange(10, 3);
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 5. Print from start up to end (forward recursion)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void printUpRange(int start, int end) {
    if (start > end) {
        return;
    }
    cout << start << "\n";
    printUpRange(start + 1, end);
}

int main() {
    printUpRange(3, 10);
    return 0;
}
```

#### 7.2 Topic - Classic Recursive Problems (sum, factorial, and more)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: arrays; strings as parameters; pointers; references; classes/objects; dynamic memory.
  - Use only: scalar parameters and return values for classic problems (sum, factorial, power, sum of digits).

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 6. Recursive sum of numbers from 1 to n
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int sumToN(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) {
        return 0;
    }
    return n + sumToN(n - 1);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter n: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "Sum from 1 to " << n << " = " << sumToN(n) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 7. Recursive factorial function
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

long long factorial(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) {
        return 1;
    }
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter n: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "Factorial of " << n << " = " << factorial(n) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 8. Recursive power: compute a^b
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

long long power(int a, int b) {
    if (b == 0) {
        return 1;
    }
    return a * power(a, b - 1);
}

int main() {
    int a, b;
    cout << "Enter base (a): ";
    cin >> a;
    cout << "Enter exponent (b): ";
    cin >> b;
    cout << a << "^" << b << " = " << power(a, b) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 9. Recursive sum of digits
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int sumOfDigits(int n) {
    if (n == 0) {
        return 0;
    }
    return (n % 10) + sumOfDigits(n / 10);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter a number: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "Sum of digits = " << sumOfDigits(n) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

