## 8. Arrays - Tutorial specs for AI (C++)

> These array topics are for **raw C-style arrays** first (e.g. `int nums[10]`), not `std::vector`.

#### 8.1 Topic - Intro to 1D Arrays (declaration, initialization, index access)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: `std::vector`; passing arrays to functions; strings as a topic; pointers (except `&` with `cin` is not used); classes/structs; dynamic allocation.
  - Use only: fixed-size C-style `int` arrays, index-based read/write first, then a simple loop to print.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Declare and initialize an array, read/write using index (no loops first)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

    cout << "First element = " << nums[0] << "\n";
    cout << "Second element = " << nums[1] << "\n";

    nums[2] = 99;
    cout << "Updated third element = " << nums[2] << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Print all elements using a for loop
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
    int size = 5;

    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        cout << "nums[" << i << "] = " << nums[i] << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

#### 8.2 Topic - Fixed-size Arrays with Loops (read, write, print)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: `std::vector`; passing arrays to functions; pointers; classes/structs; dynamic allocation.
  - Use only: `int nums[10]`, reading with `cin`, printing with loops.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 3. Read 10 integers into an array and print them (forward + backward)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[10];

    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        cout << "Enter element " << i << ": ";
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    cout << "Array elements (forward):\n";
    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        cout << nums[i] << " ";
    }
    cout << "\n";

    cout << "Array elements (backward):\n";
    for (int i = 9; i >= 0; i--) {
        cout << nums[i] << " ";
    }
    cout << "\n";

    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Print only even elements of an array
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[10];

    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        cout << "Enter element " << i << ": ";
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    cout << "Even elements:\n";
    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        if (nums[i] % 2 == 0) {
            cout << nums[i] << " ";
        }
    }
    cout << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

#### 8.3 Topic - Simple Algorithms on Arrays (max, min, bubble sort)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: `std::sort`; `std::vector`; passing arrays to functions; pointers; dynamic allocation; other sorting algorithms.
  - Use only: loops + swapping + bubble sort; max/min scan.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 5. Find maximum in an array
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[100];
    int n;
    cout << "Enter number of elements (max 100): ";
    cin >> n;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << "Enter element " << i << ": ";
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    int mx = nums[0];
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        if (nums[i] > mx) {
            mx = nums[i];
        }
    }

    cout << "Maximum value = " << mx << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 6. Find minimum in an array
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[100];
    int n;
    cout << "Enter number of elements (max 100): ";
    cin >> n;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << "Enter element " << i << ": ";
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    int mn = nums[0];
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        if (nums[i] < mn) {
            mn = nums[i];
        }
    }

    cout << "Minimum value = " << mn << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 7. Bubble sort in ascending order
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[100];
    int n;
    cout << "Enter number of elements (max 100): ";
    cin >> n;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << "Enter element " << i << ": ";
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - 1 - i; j++) {
            if (nums[j] > nums[j + 1]) {
                int temp = nums[j];
                nums[j] = nums[j + 1];
                nums[j + 1] = temp;
            }
        }
    }

    cout << "Sorted array:\n";
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << nums[i] << " ";
    }
    cout << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

#### 8.4 Topic - 2D Arrays (brief intro)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: `std::vector<vector<int>>`; passing arrays to functions; pointers to rows; dynamic allocation.
  - Use only: fixed small `int a[2][3]` style arrays, nested loops, `cin/cout`.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Declare and initialize a 2x3 array, then print it
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[2][3] = {
        {1, 2, 3},
        {4, 5, 6}
    };

    cout << "2x3 matrix values:\n";
    for (int row = 0; row < 2; row++) {
        for (int col = 0; col < 3; col++) {
            cout << nums[row][col] << " ";
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Read values into a 2x3 array from user, then print
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int nums[2][3];

    for (int row = 0; row < 2; row++) {
        for (int col = 0; col < 3; col++) {
            cout << "Enter element [" << row << "][" << col << "]: ";
            cin >> nums[row][col];
        }
    }

    cout << "You entered:\n";
    for (int row = 0; row < 2; row++) {
        for (int col = 0; col < 3; col++) {
            cout << nums[row][col] << " ";
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

