## 10. Pointers - Tutorial specs for AI (C++)

### 10.1 Topic - Addresses and Basic int Pointers

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: pointer arithmetic; arrays-and-pointers relationship; references; passing pointers to functions (pass-by-reference); pointers to classes/structs; `new/delete`; smart pointers.
  - Use only: `&` (address-of), `*` (dereference), `int *p`, printing addresses with `cout` (or `printf("%p")` only if explicitly allowed in this topic), and changing a single `int` through a pointer.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Print address of a variable
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int x = 10;
    cout << "Value of x = " << x << "\n";
    cout << "Address of x = " << &x << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Storing an address in a pointer
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int x = 10;
    int *ptr = &x;

    cout << "Value of x = " << x << "\n";
    cout << "Value via *ptr = " << *ptr << "\n";
    cout << "Address of x = " << &x << "\n";
    cout << "Value of ptr = " << ptr << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Two normal variables: copying values (independent)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = a;

    cout << "Initially: a = " << a << ", b = " << b << "\n";
    a = 20;
    cout << "After changing a: a = " << a << ", b = " << b << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Pointer: changing through pointer affects original variable
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int *p = &a;

    cout << "Initially: a = " << a << ", *p = " << *p << "\n";
    *p = 20;
    cout << "After *p = 20: a = " << a << ", *p = " << *p << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 5. Using pointer to copy value from one variable to another
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int source = 42;
    int dest = 0;
    int *p = &source;

    cout << "Before copy: source = " << source << ", dest = " << dest << "\n";
    dest = *p;
    cout << "After copy: source = " << source << ", dest = " << dest << "\n";

    source = 100;
    cout << "After changing source: source = " << source << ", dest = " << dest << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

