## 11. Structures / Classes - Tutorial specs for AI (C++)

### 11.1 Topic - Why `struct`? (grouping related data)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: classes with methods; constructors; private/public details beyond basics; pointers to structs; `->`; dynamic allocation; inheritance.
  - Use only: `struct` with public fields, `.` member access, arrays of structs, read/print fields with `cin/cout`.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Managing student data with separate variables (hard to scale)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    string student1Name = "Alice";
    int student1Age = 18;
    float student1Marks = 92.5f;

    string student2Name = "Bob";
    int student2Age = 19;
    float student2Marks = 85.0f;

    cout << "Student 1: " << student1Name << ", Age: " << student1Age << ", Marks: " << student1Marks << "\n";
    cout << "Student 2: " << student2Name << ", Age: " << student2Age << ", Marks: " << student2Marks << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Using struct to group student data
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

struct Student {
    string name;
    int age;
    float marks;
};

int main() {
    Student s1 = {"Alice", 18, 92.5f};
    Student s2 = {"Bob", 19, 85.0f};

    cout << "Student 1: " << s1.name << ", Age: " << s1.age << ", Marks: " << s1.marks << "\n";
    cout << "Student 2: " << s2.name << ", Age: " << s2.age << ", Marks: " << s2.marks << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Array of structures: multiple students
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

struct Student {
    string name;
    int age;
    float marks;
};

int main() {
    Student students[3] = {
        {"Alice", 18, 92.5f},
        {"Bob", 19, 85.0f},
        {"Carol", 20, 78.0f}
    };

    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        cout << "Student " << (i + 1) << ": " << students[i].name
             << ", Age: " << students[i].age
             << ", Marks: " << students[i].marks << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Reading one student from user input
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

struct Student {
    string name;
    int age;
    float marks;
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    cout << "Enter name: ";
    cin >> s.name;
    cout << "Enter age: ";
    cin >> s.age;
    cout << "Enter marks: ";
    cin >> s.marks;

    cout << "You entered: " << s.name << ", Age: " << s.age << ", Marks: " << s.marks << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

### 11.2 Topic - More `struct` Examples (Car, Animal, etc.)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: `->`; pointers to structs; dynamic allocation; member functions; operator overloading.
  - Use only: plain `struct` with fields and loops over arrays of structs.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
