## 13. OOP - Tutorial specs for AI (C++)

> **Pending tutorials requested here**: create **1 intro OOP tutorial**, with **4"6 lessons**, that introduces: what OOP means at a beginner level, **classes vs structs in C++**, and **classes and objects**. Follow the lesson structure: concept -> mcq -> codeblock_rearranging -> fill_in_blanks, with small C++ snippets, `keyPoints`, `commonMistakes`, `bestPractices`, and `practiceHints`.

### 13.1 Topic - Intro to OOP: Classes vs Structs, Classes & Objects

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: access specifiers as a full topic (`private`, `protected`, "access control rules", getters/setters, encapsulation); constructors/destructors; member function overloading; `this` pointer; inheritance/polymorphism; templates; `new/delete`; smart pointers.
  - Use only: `class` and `struct` definitions with **public** members (use the `public` keyword inside classes), creating objects, assigning to fields, reading fields, and printing results with `cout`. You may mention that classes/structs differ in defaults in a single sentence, but do not teach access specifiers here.
- **Core concepts**
  - OOP idea for beginners: "model real-world things as objects with data."
  - A **class** is a blueprint; an **object** is a variable created from that blueprint.
  - In C++, both `struct` and `class` can hold data members; beginners often start with `struct`, but `class` is commonly used for OOP.
  - In this topic, always use `public` so learners can access fields without learning access control yet.
- **Lesson breakdown (4"6 lessons)**
  - L1 (concept): What is a class? What is an object? Create 1 object and print its fields.
  - L2 (concept): Class vs struct with the same example; show that both can store grouped data.
  - L3 (concept): Multiple objects of the same class; changing one object doesn't change another.
  - L4 (mcq): Predict output / choose correct declaration / identify object vs class.
  - L5 (codeblock_rearranging): Rearrange blocks to build a minimal class + object program.
  - L6 (fill_in_blanks): Fill missing `class`, `public`, object name, member access `.`.
- **Common mistakes**
  - Forgetting the semicolon after the class/struct definition (`};`).
  - Forgetting `public:` inside a `class` and then being unable to access members.
  - Confusing the class name with an object (e.g., trying to use `Student.name` instead of `s.name`).
- **Best practices (for this beginner topic)**
  - Use meaningful names (`Student`, `Car`).
  - Keep examples tiny: 2"3 fields, 1"2 objects.
  - Always use braces `{ ... }` for `if`/`for` bodies in examples.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Class and object (use public keyword)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;
    float marks;
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    s.name = "Alice";
    s.age = 18;
    s.marks = 92.5f;

    cout << "Name: " << s.name << ", Age: " << s.age << ", Marks: " << s.marks << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Struct vs class: both group related data
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

struct ProductStruct {
    string name;
    int price;
};

class ProductClass {
public:
    string name;
    int price;
};

int main() {
    ProductStruct p1;
    p1.name = "Pen";
    p1.price = 10;

    ProductClass p2;
    p2.name = "Notebook";
    p2.price = 50;

    cout << p1.name << " costs " << p1.price << "\n";
    cout << p2.name << " costs " << p2.price << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Multiple objects from the same class
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Car {
public:
    string brand;
    int year;
};

int main() {
    Car c1;
    c1.brand = "Toyota";
    c1.year = 2020;

    Car c2;
    c2.brand = "Honda";
    c2.year = 2019;

    c1.year = 2021; // change only c1

    cout << "Car 1: " << c1.brand << " " << c1.year << "\n";
    cout << "Car 2: " << c2.brand << " " << c2.year << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Input into an object (still public fields, no constructors)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class User {
public:
    string username;
    int age;
};

int main() {
    User u;
    cout << "Enter username: ";
    cin >> u.username;
    cout << "Enter age: ";
    cin >> u.age;

    cout << "User: " << u.username << ", Age: " << u.age << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

---

### 13.2 Topic - Class Methods (member functions): no params/return -> params/return -> setAll + display

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: constructors/destructors; inheritance/polymorphism; virtual functions; templates; `this` pointer (as a separate concept); operator overloading; `new/delete`; smart pointers.
  - Do **not** teach "access specifiers" as a theory topic (public/private/protected rules in depth).
  - Use only: classes with member functions, calling methods on objects with `.`, methods with:
    - no parameters + no return (`void`)
    - parameters only (`void`)
    - return only (no parameters)
    - both parameters and return
  - Do **not** use `private` in examples. Keep fields public and demonstrate a single "set all values" method + a single display method.

- **Core concepts**
  - A **method** (member function) is a function written **inside** a class and called using an object: `obj.method();`
  - Methods let you keep "related behavior" next to the data (class fields).
  - Progression for beginners:
    - `void` method: does something (prints)
    - method with parameters: takes input
    - method with return: gives output
    - set-all + display methods: update and show object data

- **Lesson breakdown (4"6 lessons)**
  - L1 (concept): Method with **no parameters and no return** (demo class).
  - L2 (concept): Method with **parameters only** (prints or updates something).
  - L3 (concept): Method with **return only** (simple computed value).
  - L4 (concept): Method with **parameters + return** (e.g., calculate total price).
  - L5 (concept): Meaningful "set all values" + "display" methods on `Student`.
  - L6 (concept): Meaningful "set all values" + "display" methods on `Car`.
  - Add MCQ + rearranging + fill-in-blanks exercises after each concept chunk.

- **Common mistakes**
  - Forgetting parentheses when calling a method (writing `obj.print;` instead of `obj.print();`).
  - Forgetting the class semicolon `};`.
  - Writing a method outside the class but forgetting `ClassName::` (you can mention this exists, but keep examples inside the class for now).

- **Best practices (for this beginner topic)**
  - Keep method names verb-like: `display`, `setData`, `printInfo`.
  - Keep methods short; use braces for every `if` and loop.
  - Prefer meaningful examples (Student, Car) over random math-only methods.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Demo class method: no parameters, no return (void)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Greeter {
public:
    void sayHello() {
        cout << "Hello Codehub\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Greeter g;
    g.sayHello();
    g.sayHello();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Method with parameter only (void)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Printer {
public:
    void printNTimes(int n) {
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            cout << "Hello\n";
        }
    }
};

int main() {
    Printer p;
    p.printNTimes(3);
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Method with return only (no parameters)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Dice {
public:
    int getFixedRoll() {
        return 6;
    }
};

int main() {
    Dice d;
    cout << "Roll = " << d.getFixedRoll() << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Method with parameters + return
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Calculator {
public:
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
};

int main() {
    Calculator c;
    cout << "Sum = " << c.add(10, 20) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 5. Student: one setData() + one display() (no private)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;
    float marks;

    void setData(string newName, int newAge, float newMarks) {
        name = newName;
        age = newAge;
        marks = newMarks;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Name: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", Marks: " << marks << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    s.setData("Alice", 18, 92.5f);
    s.display();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 6. Car: one setData() + one display() (no private)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Car {
public:
    string brand;
    int year;
    float price;

    void setData(string newBrand, int newYear, float newPrice) {
        brand = newBrand;
        year = newYear;
        price = newPrice;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Car: " << brand << ", Year: " << year << ", Price: " << price << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Car c;
    c.setData("Toyota", 2020, 15000.0f);
    c.display();
    return 0;
}
```

---

### 13.3 Topic - Constructors (object creation + constructor runs automatically)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: destructors; copy constructor; copy assignment; move semantics; `this` pointer (as a separate concept); inheritance/polymorphism; templates; `new/delete`; smart pointers.
  - Do **not** teach "access specifiers" as a theory topic (public/private/protected rules in depth). Keep everything `public` in examples.
  - Use only: default constructor (no parameters) and parameterized constructor (sets fields), object creation, and a simple `display()` method.

- **Core concepts**
  - A **constructor** is a special function with the **same name as the class**.
  - Constructor has **no return type** (not even `void`).
  - A constructor runs **automatically when an object is created**.
  - Goal for beginners: see "constructor runs on object creation" clearly, then use constructors to set initial values.

- **Lesson breakdown (4"6 lessons)**
  - L1 (concept): Default constructor prints a message like "Object created" to prove it runs on creation.
  - L2 (concept): Parameterized constructor sets all fields (like a "setter constructor") + `display()`.
  - L3 (concept): Create multiple objects; show constructor runs each time.
  - L4 (mcq): Predict output order: constructor message vs display output; identify valid constructor syntax.
  - L5 (codeblock_rearranging): Rearrange blocks to build a class with constructor + display.
  - L6 (fill_in_blanks): Fill missing constructor name, parentheses, object creation line, and `display()` call.

- **Common mistakes**
  - Writing a return type for the constructor (`void Student()`) - invalid.
  - Forgetting `;` after class definition.
  - Naming constructor incorrectly (must match class name exactly).

- **Best practices (for this beginner topic)**
  - Keep constructors simple: just set fields and maybe print a short message for learning.
  - Use meaningful classes like `Student`, `Car`.
  - Keep examples small (2"3 fields) and always use braces for loops/if bodies.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Default constructor demo: runs automatically on object creation
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Demo {
public:
    Demo() {
        cout << "Demo object created\n";
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "display() called\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Demo d;        // constructor runs here
    d.display();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Student: parameterized constructor sets all values + display
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;
    float marks;

    Student(string n, int a, float m) {
        cout << "Student object created\n";
        name = n;
        age = a;
        marks = m;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Name: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", Marks: " << marks << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s("Alice", 18, 92.5f);
    s.display();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Car: parameterized constructor + multiple objects
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Car {
public:
    string brand;
    int year;
    float price;

    Car(string b, int y, float p) {
        cout << "Car object created\n";
        brand = b;
        year = y;
        price = p;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Car: " << brand << ", Year: " << year << ", Price: " << price << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Car c1("Toyota", 2020, 15000.0f);
    Car c2("Honda", 2019, 14000.0f);

    c1.display();
    c2.display();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Default + parameterized constructors together (intro)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class User {
public:
    string username;
    int age;

    User() {
        cout << "User object created (default)\n";
        username = "unknown";
        age = 0;
    }

    User(string u, int a) {
        cout << "User object created (with data)\n";
        username = u;
        age = a;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "User: " << username << ", Age: " << age << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    User u1;               // default constructor
    User u2("Rahul", 20);  // parameterized constructor

    u1.display();
    u2.display();
    return 0;
}
```

---

### 13.4 Topic - Encapsulation: `public` vs `private` (why private matters)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: `protected` (save it for after inheritance); inheritance/polymorphism; virtual functions; operator overloading; templates; `new/delete`; smart pointers.
  - Use only: `public` and `private`, simple classes, object creation, and public methods that safely change private data.

- **Core concepts**
  - `public`: members can be accessed from outside the class using `obj.member` or `obj.method()`.
  - `private`: members cannot be accessed from outside the class. Only class methods can use them.
  - Why `private` is needed: it prevents "anyone can change anything" and forces updates through valid actions (deposit/withdraw, updateMarks with validation, applyDiscount, etc.).

- **Lesson breakdown (4"6 lessons)**
  - L1 (concept): Demo class showing what works with `public` and what is blocked with `private`.
  - L2 (concept): Student example: keep marks private, change through a public method (basic validation).
  - L3 (concept): Car example: keep price private, update using a public method (basic validation).
  - L4 (concept): Real-world analogy: ATM balance cannot be changed directly; only deposit/withdraw are allowed.
  - L5 (mcq): Choose correct access, predict which lines cause compile error.
  - L6 (rearrange + FIB): Build a class with one private field and two public methods.

- **Common mistakes**
  - Expecting `obj.privateField` to work (it won't compile).
  - Putting everything in `public` and losing control of data changes.
  - Forgetting `private:` / `public:` labels or forgetting the class semicolon `};`.

- **Best practices (for this beginner topic)**
  - Make important values private (balance, marks, price, password).
  - Provide public methods that represent valid actions (deposit/withdraw, updateMarks, applyDiscount, changePassword).
  - Keep validations simple at this stage.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. Demo: public vs private
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class DemoAccess {
public:
    int publicValue;

private:
    int secretValue;

public:
    void setSecretValue(int v) {
        secretValue = v;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "publicValue = " << publicValue << "\n";
        cout << "secretValue = " << secretValue << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    DemoAccess d;
    d.publicValue = 10;     // OK (public)
    // d.secretValue = 99;  // NOT OK (private) - would not compile

    d.setSecretValue(99);   // OK (public method)
    d.display();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Student: keep marks private, update via public method (simple validation)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Student {
public:
    string name;
    int age;

private:
    float marks;

public:
    Student(string n, int a, float m) {
        name = n;
        age = a;
        marks = m;
    }

    void updateMarks(float newMarks) {
        if (newMarks < 0.0f || newMarks > 100.0f) {
            cout << "Invalid marks\n";
            return;
        }
        marks = newMarks;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Name: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", Marks: " << marks << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s("Alice", 18, 92.5f);
    // s.marks = 200; // NOT OK (private)
    s.updateMarks(95.0f);
    s.display();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Car: keep price private, update via public method
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Car {
public:
    string brand;
    int year;

private:
    float price;

public:
    Car(string b, int y, float p) {
        brand = b;
        year = y;
        price = p;
    }

    void applyDiscount(float percent) {
        if (percent < 0.0f || percent > 100.0f) {
            cout << "Invalid discount\n";
            return;
        }
        price = price - (price * percent / 100.0f);
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "Car: " << brand << ", Year: " << year << ", Price: " << price << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Car c("Toyota", 2020, 15000.0f);
    // c.price = 1; // NOT OK (private)
    c.applyDiscount(10.0f);
    c.display();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. Meaningful example: ATM balance cannot be changed directly
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class ATMAccount {
private:
    int balance;

public:
    ATMAccount(int initialBalance) {
        balance = initialBalance;
    }

    void deposit(int amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) {
            cout << "Invalid deposit amount\n";
            return;
        }
        balance += amount;
    }

    void withdraw(int amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) {
            cout << "Invalid withdraw amount\n";
            return;
        }
        if (amount > balance) {
            cout << "Insufficient balance\n";
            return;
        }
        balance -= amount;
    }

    void showBalance() {
        cout << "Balance = " << balance << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    ATMAccount acc(1000);
    // acc.balance = 999999; // NOT OK (private)

    acc.showBalance();
    acc.deposit(500);
    acc.withdraw(200);
    acc.showBalance();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 5. Another meaningful example: password should not be directly readable/changed
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Account {
private:
    string password;

public:
    Account(string initialPassword) {
        password = initialPassword;
    }

    int checkPassword(string input) {
        return input == password;
    }

    void changePassword(string oldPass, string newPass) {
        if (oldPass != password) {
            cout << "Wrong old password\n";
            return;
        }
        password = newPass;
        cout << "Password changed\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Account a("codehub123");
    // cout << a.password; // NOT OK (private)

    if (a.checkPassword("codehub123")) {
        cout << "Login success\n";
    } else {
        cout << "Login failed\n";
    }

    a.changePassword("codehub123", "newpass");
    return 0;
}
```
 
## 14. Inheritance - Tutorial specs for AI (C++)

> **Pending tutorials requested here**: create **3"4 inheritance tutorials**, each with **4"6 lessons**, that introduce inheritance step-by-step with small, beginner-friendly C++ examples. Start with single inheritance and reusability (one base -> many derived), then multilevel inheritance, then multiple inheritance, then teach the `protected` specifier after learners understand inheritance. Keep methods multi-line and use examples with multiple meaningful properties.

### 14.1 Topic - Inheritance Basics (Single inheritance + reusability)

- **Exclusions (do not teach or mention in this topic)**
  - Do **not** introduce or reference: multilevel inheritance; multiple inheritance; `protected` (separate topic later); virtual functions; overriding keywords (`override`, `final`); polymorphism; abstract classes; constructors in inheritance (base/derived constructor chaining); templates; `new/delete`.
  - Use only: `class Base { ... }`, `class Derived : public Base { ... }`, public inheritance, calling base methods from derived objects, and showing "code reuse".

- **Core concepts**
  - Inheritance means: a child class **reuses** (inherits) fields/methods from a parent class.
  - Syntax: `class Child : public Parent { ... };`
  - Reusability: when many types share common data/behavior (Student/Teacher share User fields), put common parts in the base class.

- **Lesson breakdown (4"6 lessons)**
  - L1 (concept): DemoParent -> DemoChild basic inheritance.
  - L2 (concept): User -> Student.
  - L3 (concept): Vehicle -> Car.
  - L4 (concept): One base -> many derived: User -> Student/Teacher and Vehicle -> Car/Bike/Truck.
  - L5 (mcq): identify base vs derived; which members are inherited; predict output.
  - L6 (rearrange + FIB): build base+derived skeleton and fill `: public Base`.

- **Example snippets**

```cpp
// 1. DemoParent and DemoChild (single inheritance)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class DemoParent {
public:
    void parentMsg() {
        cout << "I am Parent\n";
    }
};

class DemoChild : public DemoParent {
public:
    void childMsg() {
        cout << "I am Child\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    DemoChild c;
    c.parentMsg();
    c.childMsg();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 2. Application: User-Student (multiple properties)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class User {
public:
    string name;
    int age;
    string phone;

    void setUser(string n, int a, string p) {
        name = n;
        age = a;
        phone = p;
    }

    void displayUser() {
        cout << "Name: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", Phone: " << phone << "\n";
    }
};

class Student : public User {
public:
    int rollNo;
    float marks;

    void setStudent(int r, float m) {
        rollNo = r;
        marks = m;
    }

    void displayStudent() {
        displayUser();
        cout << "RollNo: " << rollNo << ", Marks: " << marks << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    s.setUser("Alice", 18, "9999999999");
    s.setStudent(101, 92.5f);
    s.displayStudent();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 3. Application: Vehicle-Car (multiple properties)
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class Vehicle {
public:
    string brand;
    int wheels;
    int speed;

    void setVehicle(string b, int w, int s) {
        brand = b;
        wheels = w;
        speed = s;
    }

    void displayVehicle() {
        cout << "Brand: " << brand << ", Wheels: " << wheels << ", Speed: " << speed << "\n";
    }
};

class Car : public Vehicle {
public:
    int doors;
    string fuel;

    void setCar(int d, string f) {
        doors = d;
        fuel = f;
    }

    void displayCar() {
        displayVehicle();
        cout << "Doors: " << doors << ", Fuel: " << fuel << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Car c;
    c.setVehicle("Toyota", 4, 120);
    c.setCar(4, "Petrol");
    c.displayCar();
    return 0;
}
```

```cpp
// 4. One base, many children: User-Student-Teacher and Vehicle-Car-Bike-Truck
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

class User {
public:
    string name;
    int age;
    string city;

    void setUser(string n, int a, string c) {
        name = n;
        age = a;
        city = c;
    }

    void displayUser() {
        cout << "Name: " << name << ", Age: " << age << ", City: " << city << "\n";
    }
};

class Student : public User {
public:
    int rollNo;
    string course;

    void setStudent(int r, string c) {
        rollNo = r;
        course = c;
    }

    void displayStudent() {
        displayUser();
        cout << "RollNo: " << rollNo << ", Course: " << course << "\n";
    }
};

class Teacher : public User {
public:
    string subject;
    int experienceYears;

    void setTeacher(string sub, int exp) {
        subject = sub;
        experienceYears = exp;
    }

    void displayTeacher() {
        displayUser();
        cout << "Subject: " << subject << ", Experience: " << experienceYears << " years\n";
    }
};

class Vehicle {
public:
    string brand;
    int wheels;
    int maxSpeed;

    void setVehicle(string b, int w, int s) {
        brand = b;
        wheels = w;
        maxSpeed = s;
    }

    void displayVehicle() {
        cout << "Brand: " << brand << ", Wheels: " << wheels << ", MaxSpeed: " << maxSpeed << "\n";
    }
};

class Car : public Vehicle {
public:
    int doors;
    string fuel;

    void setCar(int d, string f) {
        doors = d;
        fuel = f;
    }

    void displayCar() {
        displayVehicle();
        cout << "Doors: " << doors << ", Fuel: " << fuel << "\n";
    }
};

class Bike : public Vehicle {
public:
    int cc;
    int hasGear;

    void setBike(int engineCc, int gear) {
        cc = engineCc;
        hasGear = gear;
    }

    void displayBike() {
        displayVehicle();
        cout << "CC: " << cc << ", GearBike: ";
        if (hasGear) {
            cout << "Yes";
        } else {
            cout << "No";
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }
};

class Truck : public Vehicle {
public:
    int loadCapacityKg;
    int axles;

    void setTruck(int loadKg, int a) {
        loadCapacityKg = loadKg;
        axles = a;
    }

    void displayTruck() {
        displayVehicle();
        cout << "Load: " << loadCapacityKg << "kg, Axles: " << axles << "\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s;
    s.setUser("Ravi", 19, "Pune");
    s.setStudent(10, "C++");
    s.displayStudent();

    Teacher t;
    t.setUser("Meena", 30, "Delhi");
    t.setTeacher("Math", 7);
    t.displayTeacher();

    Car c;
    c.setVehicle("Toyota", 4, 180);
    c.setCar(4, "Petrol");
    c.displayCar();

    Bike b;
    b.setVehicle("Yamaha", 2, 140);
    b.setBike(150, 1);
    b.displayBike();

    Truck tr;
    tr.setVehicle("Tata", 6, 120);
    tr.setTruck(8000, 2);
    tr.displayTruck();

    return 0;
}
```

